Beyond OpenAI: The Quiet Rise of Decentralized Intelligence

Mohamed Allam

Jun 12, 2025 ⋅  33 min read

Key Insights

  • Innovations such as Pluralis’s structured subspace compression, Nous’s DisTrO optimizer, Prime Intellect’s asynchronous reinforcement learning, and Gensyn’s collaborative RL Swarm prove that large-scale model training can happen across distributed, unreliable hardware with minimal bandwidth. Once considered impossible, technical breakthroughs have made decentralized training feasible.
  • UX matters more than ideology; ChatGPT’s dominance is as much about usability as model quality. Clunky interfaces and confusing onboarding will kill adoption. Projects must compete on frontend experience, not just backend philosophy.
  • Economic impact doesn’t require market dominance; decentralized AI does not need to beat OpenAI outright. Even a small slice of the projected $15.7 trillion AI market would support a thriving ecosystem. Like open source, it can succeed as critical infrastructure.
  • Coexistence > Confrontation. The goal isn’t to replace Big AI, it’s to offer what it cannot: transparency, community ownership, and trustless coordination. As Sun Tzu said, “Avoid what is strong. Attack what is weak.” Decentralized AI should focus on niches that Big AI won’t serve.

Primer: Why Decentralized AI Is Emerging Now

Artificial intelligence is evolving rapidly, toward a future where no facet of society will remain untouched. As outlined in the AI 2027 report series, the technology is nearing an inflection point, with profound implications for intelligence, labor markets, and national security. Unlike past industrial shifts, this transformation extends beyond the workplace or battlefield. It touches the very structure of human systems: how decisions are made, how knowledge is distributed, and eventually how we think and learn. Society stands on the edge of a comprehensive reordering. This shift is technological, political, and cultural, all driven by increasingly powerful forms of machine intelligence.

At the same time, another global shift is underway. After years of experimentation, decentralized finance is starting to gain widespread attention and adoption. Built as a response to the concentration of power in traditional financial institutions, decentralized finance introduced a model of open participation, user sovereignty, and permissionless innovation. That same ethos is now informing a parallel development in artificial intelligence. As control over powerful models becomes increasingly consolidated and limited to a few private labs and platforms, a growing number of researchers, developers, and communities are beginning to ask:

  1. What does it mean when access to intelligence is gated by corporate policy?
  2. What happens when models are trained on data the public cannot audit, governed by policies users cannot influence, and deployed in systems they cannot interrogate?
  3. Can any institution, no matter how well-intentioned, be trusted to manage intelligence at a global scale without transparency or accountability?

In response, a growing segment of developers, researchers, and communities are working to build an open alternative. There is increasing demand for AI systems that are transparent, participatory, and accountable. The infrastructure that emerged from crypto, like networks that enable permissionless coordination, decentralized compute, and incentive alignment, is now being extended to support a vision of open and decentralized AI. What was originally built for financial sovereignty is proving just as relevant for the governance and deployment of intelligent systems.

This report explores that shift through four projects leading the way in decentralized AI development: Pluralis Research, Nous Research, Gensyn, and Prime Intellect. These aren’t the only ones. Others like Flock (decentralized training), Grass (data), Kled (data), Nosana (compute), and Ritual (infrastructure) are also contributing across different layers of the stack. The report begins with a brief history of decentralized AI, followed by an explanation of centralized AI, how decentralized AI differs, and an overview of current projects, along with an assessment of their economic feasibility. This report is written in plain English to make every concept accessible, so that by the end, you walk away with a clear understanding of how decentralized AI works, why it is important, and what it will take for it to succeed.

The thesis is straightforward

“Decentralized AI will not replace OpenAI or Anthropic or any of the major corporate players. It does not need to. What it can do is create an alternative path where models are not only accessible and auditable, but governed and owned by the communities that rely on them. In doing so, it will carve out meaningful and defensible niches in the AI ecosystem. Even if decentralized AI comes to represent only a fraction of the total market, that fraction will be significant enough to shape the future of how intelligence is developed, deployed, and distributed.”

A Brief History of Decentralized AI

In the opening of The Singularity Is Near, Ray Kurzweil makes a simple but powerful point: revolutionary ideas often fail not because they lack merit but because the timing is wrong. The market has to be ready, the infrastructure has to be there, and people need to care.

In 2017, SingularityNET launched with ambitious plans to build a decentralized marketplace for AI services. It was led by experienced researchers and built around a forward-looking thesis, but the ecosystem was not yet ready. Public interest in AI was limited, and the crypto space lacked the scalability and tools necessary to support coordination on the scale required. Ocean Protocol, which focused on decentralized data sharing, faced a similar situation. While both projects remain active, they have struggled to achieve mainstream traction. In June 2024, SingularityNET, Ocean Protocol, and Fetch.ai officially finalized a merger to form the Artificial Superintelligence Alliance, uniting their efforts under a shared vision with the aim of making a comeback with better timing.

Everything changed in late 2022 when OpenAI launched ChatGPT. The product reached one million users in five days. To put that into perspective, Instagram took 2.5 months, Spotify took five months, and Netflix took three and a half years. ChatGPT was not just a breakthrough; it was a cultural inflection point. For the first time, the general public could interact with a powerful language model in real time. AI went from being an abstract research field to a tangible force in everyday life, and with that spotlight came scrutiny.

As OpenAI and others began rolling out larger, more capable models behind closed doors, frustration started to mount. GPT-4 arrived on March 14, 2023, with no details about its training data, architecture, or inner workings. API access was limited, and usage was increasingly constrained by invisible rules. People began asking harder questions, not just about what these systems could do, but about who controlled them.

At the same time, a new generation of decentralized infrastructure began to mature. Akash Network offered a decentralized alternative to cloud computing. Filecoin and Arweave provided scalable, censorship-resistant storage. Bittensor, Gensyn, and IO.net began enabling distributed model training and inference. This tooling gave decentralized AI something it had long lacked: a complete infrastructure stack. It also brought new visibility to the broader movement. For years, the crypto space was viewed mainly as a financial innovation. Now, for the first time, its infrastructure, referred to as Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks or DePIN, a term introduced by Messari, was playing a visible and meaningful role in another major technological frontier: artificial intelligence.

The shift was not only technical. It was cultural and geopolitical. As tensions around the world grew and conversations about power, surveillance, and economic control intensified, the centralization of AI started to feel increasingly risky. People began to sense that something more than innovation was at stake. With AI influencing elections, markets, education, and media, the idea that it should be developed and governed by just a handful of private labs became harder to defend.

Decentralized AI began to make more sense, not just as a technological preference, but as a political and social imperative. Fear is a powerful motivator, and in a time of growing distrust, decentralized intelligence offers an alternative that aligns with calls for transparency, control, and collective ownership. It is no longer just a fringe ideal. It is a practical counterbalance.

The key shift is this: decentralized AI has moved from an early vision, mostly theoretical, to a wave of production-ready experiments with real coordination, economic layers, and accelerating demand. For the first time, it has the infrastructure, the public interest, and the cultural timing to matter.

AI 101: Understanding the Core Concepts

Before diving into the projects, let’s take a step back and understand how large language models (LLMs) are made and why the current approach is highly centralized.

At a high level, building an AI model like ChatGPT or Claude involves four major stages: pretraining, fine-tuning, post-training, and inference. Each of these steps not only requires powerful infrastructure but is also typically controlled by a small number of well-funded companies. Understanding how these stages work helps clarify why decentralization matters.

Pretraining: The Foundation Layer

The journey starts with pretraining. This is the process of teaching a model general knowledge by feeding it vast amounts of data such as books, websites, Wikipedia, codebases, and more. The goal here is not to make the model great at one thing, but to give it a broad understanding of the world.

Only a handful of companies have the resources to do this. Training a model like GPT from scratch can cost tens of millions of dollars and require thousands of top-tier GPUs running for weeks. The data used is usually kept private. No one outside the company knows what the model saw, which creates risks around bias, misuse, and censorship.

Example: Imagine a few companies are the only ones with access to all the knowledge in the world. They get to read every book, analyze every dataset, and train their models with this unmatched information advantage. Everyone else only has fragments, small snippets of data scattered across the internet, with no means to compile or learn from it in a meaningful way. This imbalance gives those companies an overwhelming head start in building powerful AI systems, while keeping the foundational knowledge behind closed doors.

Fine-Tuning: Specialization and Control

Once the model has learned general patterns, the next step is fine-tuning. This means taking the pretrained model and training it further on a more specific dataset. For example, if you want the model to be good at legal analysis, you feed it court documents and legal textbooks. If you want it to help with customer service, you train it on support transcripts. This fine-tuning also tends to happen behind closed doors. The companies doing it choose which data to use, how the model should behave, and what use cases are allowed.

Example: Consider a student who has completed general education. Now, they are choosing a major, but instead of picking for themselves, a corporation decides what field they should study based on commercial goals.

Post Training: Making Sure It Plays Nice

After fine-tuning comes alignment. This is where companies try to make sure the model behaves appropriately, responding helpfully, avoiding harmful topics, and generally staying within guardrails. Techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback are used here. Humans rate the model’s answers, and those ratings help refine its future behavior.

While alignment improves model outputs, it also introduces even more control by limiting the usage of certain language or outputting material that goes against pre-determined policies. It is not always clear what values are being enforced, who is doing the rating, or how much influence users actually have in shaping model behavior.

Example: Who Sets the Boundaries of Truth? A model trained under the Chinese Communist Party will likely have very different censorship rules than one created at Google. This is not to say one is better than the other, but both operate with preset boundaries defined behind closed doors. The user has no role in deciding what is right or wrong. Instead, they are interacting with a system governed by someone else’s assumptions and values. Over time, this can subtly shape how people think, without them ever realizing it.

Inference: Using the Model in Real Life

This is the step where users finally interact with the model, asking it questions, generating images, summarizing documents, or writing code. This is called inference.

Even here, centralization plays a role. Most major models are hosted by the companies that built them. You do not download or run the model locally; you send a request to their servers, and they send back a response. They track what and how much you use the model and can block access at any time. Usage is tied to APIs, logins, and subscription tiers.

Example: What Happens When Access Is Taken Away? Imagine building an application that relies on an external API like OpenAI’s for real-time language generation. If the provider decides to change its terms, introduce usage caps, or revoke access entirely, your product breaks overnight. You have no fallback, no say in the decision, and no visibility into how or why it happened. In a world where AI will play a critical role in daily life, this kind of dependence is more than just an inconvenience; it is dangerous. Access to intelligence becomes a privilege, not a right, controlled at the discretion of a single entity.

Compute and Infrastructure: The Real Bottleneck

All of the above steps require compute, specialized processing power that is expensive, scarce, and difficult to scale. The most advanced models use NVIDIA H100 or A100 chips, which are controlled by a small number of cloud providers like Amazon, Google, or Microsoft.

Training a model requires weeks of nonstop compute. Running a model also needs servers capable of handling millions of queries per day. This is why AI development today is mostly limited to Big Tech and a few elite startups.

What Is Decentralized AI?

This is where decentralization comes in. Decentralized AI is not just about posting model weights on GitHub. It is about replacing the entire AI development pipeline with open, distributed, and user-governed systems.

Pretraining: From Solo Supercomputers to Distributed Teams

Traditionally, only a few large companies have the money and hardware to train large models from scratch. It requires thousands of GPUs and high-speed data centers. In decentralized AI, pretraining is broken into smaller pieces and shared across many machines around the world. Instead of sending large data blobs between computers, these systems use compression techniques and low-latency communication between GPUs to reduce the size and delay of the information exchanged. This allows training to happen even over slower internet connections using regular machines, not just elite hardware.

Example: Imagine assembling a giant puzzle with each person having a few pieces. Everyone works on their part, shares updates, and gradually, the full picture comes together without a single person holding it all.

Fine Tuning: Open Participation Instead of Private Labs

Once a base model is trained, it needs to be specialized for specific tasks. In centralized systems, only internal teams decide how a model gets fine-tuned and for what purpose. In decentralized systems, fine-tuning can be guided by the community. People can contribute datasets, help steer the direction of improvements, or train the model locally on specific skills and then share the results with the network.

Example: It is like learning a language in school and then practicing with people from different professions, such as scientists, chefs, and doctors, so you can speak more fluently in different areas.

Post Training (Alignment): Shared Values Instead of Hidden Guardrails

Post-training adjusts the model’s behavior: what it is allowed to say, how it responds, and what values it follows. In the centralized world, this step is done quietly and internally. Users have little control over what gets filtered or flagged. In decentralized AI, alignment can be open and community-driven. Feedback comes from users, not just hired raters. In some cases, the model’s behavior can be adjusted based on voting, staking, or provable rules everyone agrees on.

Example: This turns alignment into something transparent, more like writing a community guideline than enforcing a secret rulebook.

Inference: Using the Model Without Gatekeepers

Inference is when users actually interact with the model by asking questions, generating text, and more. In centralized systems, you send a request to a company’s server, and it returns an answer. They control access, monitor usage, and can block you at any time. In a decentralized setup, models are hosted across many nodes. Anyone with a good connection and a GPU can serve the model, and users can choose where to send their requests.

Example: This makes access permissionless. No logins, no API keys, no sudden blocks. If one server disappears, another one is ready to help.

Infrastructure: A New Backbone for Intelligence

All of this relies on decentralized infrastructure. Instead of renting servers from big cloud companies, decentralized AI runs on open networks of contributors. People around the world offer up compute power, store datasets, verify outputs, and coordinate jobs. They get rewarded automatically, and no single company controls the pipeline. This creates an open foundation by design.

Example: It is like replacing a single highway with a network of backroads. If one path is blocked, traffic can reroute, adapt, and keep flowing. No one controls the map.

Some of this infrastructure is already working, and some is still in the early stages, but together, they offer a real alternative, one where intelligence can be collectively owned and steered.

What Are These Projects Building?

Projects like Pluralis, Nous Research, Prime Intellect, and Gensyn are moving beyond theory and actively developing the tools, models, and systems necessary to support decentralized AI in practice. Each has introduced significant technical innovations, such as decentralized model parallelism, low-bandwidth optimizers, asynchronous reinforcement learning, and collaborative inference systems, that form the foundation of this emerging ecosystem.

Pluralis Research

Pluralis Research is solving a long-standing technical challenge called model parallelism. This refers to the idea of splitting up a large model and training its parts on multiple machines at the same time. In traditional setups, this only works well if all the machines are connected by extremely fast internet. That is what you would find inside a cloud provider's data center. This is because training requires each machine to constantly exchange updates such as the model’s intermediate results (called activations) and the changes being learned (gradients). These updates are large, frequent, and highly sensitive to even minor delays. On normal WiFi, this usually fails.

Pluralis’s breakthrough changes that. Instead of trying to send full activations and gradients across the internet, they compress them. Specifically, they use a method called a structured subspace constraint. This is a precise mathematical way of shrinking the size of the information while still preserving what matters most for training. Or in more technical terms, this means they constrain the activations and gradients to live in a smaller space, allowing them to be heavily compressed before transmission and still be accurately reconstructed on the other side. You can think of it like sending a detailed sketch instead of a full painting. Your teammate knows exactly how to fill in the rest on their end. It is efficient. It works.

The results speak for themselves. Pluralis achieved up to 100 times better communication efficiency than traditional model parallelism. This means they could send much less data between machines without slowing down or hurting the training process. In machine learning terms, the model still reached convergence, which means it steadily improved during training and reached the same level of accuracy as a model trained in a traditional high-speed data center. They proved this at real scale by training an 8 billion parameter LLaMA model using low-end GPUs spread across different regions, all connected with regular 60 Mbps internet. That’s a far cry from the 100 Gbps speeds found in specialized data centers. Yet, the model trained in this decentralized setup performed just as well as its centralized counterpart.

What makes this approach different from other distributed AI efforts is that Pluralis splits the model itself, not just the training process. Each machine holds only part of the model and trains it collaboratively with others. No single machine holds the full model, and no central server coordinates the system.

This architecture enables protocol learning, a new way of training in which contributors retain partial ownership and share in the value of the model without ever seeing or controlling the full version. The model is trained collectively, used collectively, and monetized without needing to be released or hosted by a central actor.

Simplified takeaways in plain English:

  • Training used to require expensive servers and fast internet. Now, it can be done from regular machines on home WiFi.
  • Each machine works on a slice of the model, so they send tiny compressed updates instead of huge files.
  • No one can steal or copy the full model. No single device sees everything.
  • People anywhere can join the training process and get rewarded fairly.
  • The model is not owned by a single company. It is built and governed by the people who help create it.

Pluralis is showing that decentralized model parallel training is no longer theoretical; it is real, tested, and functional. If this system scales further, it could become a new foundation for open AI models governed by protocols, not corporations.

Prime Intellect

Prime Intellect operates on the frontier of decentralized training, pushing past theoretical limits and building systems that work in practice. Their efforts go beyond open-source models or training smaller LLMs outside data centers. They have built a functioning, permissionless infrastructure stack for decentralized AI, complete with a compute coordination protocol, a verified reasoning dataset, and reinforcement learning models that rival their centralized counterparts. In under a year, their 10 billion parameter model, INTELLECT 1, has evolved into INTELLECT 2, a 32 billion parameter system trained entirely through globally distributed reinforcement learning (a parameter is a numerical value that an AI model learns; more parameters generally mean a more capable model).

Prime Intellect claims INTELLECT 2, the first 32 billion parameter model trained asynchronously over a globally distributed network of compute contributors. What makes this effort remarkable is that reinforcement learning is notoriously difficult to decentralize. It depends on fast, constant communication between GPUs that are physically close together, so they can quickly learn from new data and adjust the model in real time. If the connection is too slow or the machines are inconsistent, the whole process breaks down. But INTELLECT 2 was trained across a global network of different machines, many unreliable, running on the everyday internet, and without any central server coordinating the work. This only worked because Prime Intellect built custom systems that let training continue even when devices were delayed, offline, or out of sync.

At the core of the system is PRIME RL, a custom framework built to let reinforcement learning happen even on slow or scattered machines. Normally, this kind of training needs two steps, running simulations (rollouts) and updating the model, to happen quickly and in sync. That works fine in a centralized data center, where all the GPUs are fast and closely connected. But it falls apart over the internet, where machines can be slow, go offline, or have different hardware. PRIME RL avoids this problem by fully separating the two steps. Machines that run simulations can keep going no matter what, while others focus on updating the model. New versions of the model are sent out when ready, meaning there’s no need to wait for everyone to catch up. This makes the whole system more flexible and able to run across devices with different speeds and reliability. To distribute these updates, they use SHARDCAST, which sends the new model weights through a tree-structured HTTP network, a setup where each machine passes the update along to a few others, like branches on a tree. It works over regular internet and doesn’t require any special cloud infrastructure. To keep the training process honest, they also built TOPLOC, a system that uses cryptographic verification to check the output from each machine. Since different GPUs might give slightly different results, TOPLOC makes sure every answer is valid before it gets used. If a machine submits incorrect data, it’s automatically rejected and penalized.

This entire process runs on a decentralized protocol testnet. However, this is not a simulation of decentralization. It is a live, operating network. Workers join by passing hardware verification and heartbeat checks. They pull tasks via containers, complete them locally, and submit their results for validation. Contributions are logged, and ownership is tracked in a way that allows for future monetization. Anyone can watch the training run in real time or join the compute pool via the dashboard.

Feeding this training pipeline is SYNTHETIC 1, a large-scale dataset of 1.4 million verified reasoning tasks across math, science, and software engineering. Each task comes with its own verifier, either unit tests, containerized evaluation environments, or judgment systems built from LLMs themselves. The GENESYS framework powers this entire process, allowing contributors to generate new data, run verification checks, and submit expansions to the dataset. Some tasks, like synthetic code understanding, are designed to break state-of-the-art models. Others, like NuminaMath and CommitPack, ground the dataset in academic and real-world domains. Taken together, SYNTHETIC 1 gives Prime Intellect a constant stream of high-quality training signals, something most decentralized projects lack entirely.

What ties this system together is a vision for decentralized intelligence markets. This is not just about training models differently. It is about building a protocol where anyone can supply compute, data, or reasoning tasks, and be compensated for doing so. All coordination is trustless. All contributions are verifiable. This stands in stark contrast to the current model, where centralized labs monopolize both the infrastructure and the downstream value of trained models. In the Prime Intellect vision, no single party owns the model. Contributors retain economic rights, and the model can be deployed without ever being extracted or released.

Simplified takeaways in plain English:

  • Turns reinforcement learning into a decentralized process by allowing training to happen asynchronously across unreliable and globally scattered devices.
  • Solves the data quality problem by generating its own high-quality, auto-verified dataset using academic reasoning challenges.
  • Builds trust in open compute systems by verifying every result before it influences the model. Bad actors are flagged and removed automatically.
  • Coordinates contributors through a live protocol that handles everything from hardware checks to job assignments, without needing a central authority.
  • Shares the value of trained models with the people who helped build them. Models are used without ever being downloaded, protecting their integrity and ensuring fair rewards.

Gensyn

Gensyn has been around since 2020 and was one of the earliest teams to explore decentralized training. However, the team remains quite elusive. There is very little publicly facing research on them, and their papers tend to be short and high-level. Despite their relative anonymity, they are working on some of the most interesting infrastructure in the decentralized AI space. Their work on RL Swarm in particular offers a glimpse into a new way of doing machine learning.

RL Swarm is their collaborative reinforcement learning system, designed to let small models train together over the Internet. Instead of relying on centralized compute farms, Gensyn proposes a swarm-based approach where each participant can run a node and contribute to the training process. The system operates through three main phases: answering, critiquing, and resolving. Each model first attempts to answer a problem independently, then critiques the answers from its peers, and finally makes a revised judgment based on that collective feedback. Imagine you and your friends are trying to solve a complex problem. Instead of solving the problem alone, you all come together to answer each question independently. It is assumed that you all already understand the material. You then share your answers with the group and begin critiquing each other’s reasoning and offering feedback. Once everyone has weighed in, you vote amongst yourselves to determine what the best final answer is. In a swarm setting, this process happens quickly and repeatedly across many participants, not just once but continuously, as models learn from each round of feedback and improve over time.

Gensyn’s RL Swarm collaborates across three nodes, each running a 1.5 billion parameter Qwen 2.5 model. These models are trained together on the GSM8K dataset and engage in structured multistage rounds of feedback. The results show that models learning in this way perform better and reach higher accuracy with fewer training steps. The feedback loop from peer critique pushes the models to reason more clearly, structure their answers better, and become more concise in how they express solutions. Importantly, this is all done over normal internet connections on consumer-grade hardware, with no centralized clusters required.

One of the clearest ways to understand this system is through the lens of regret, a concept borrowed from game theory. Regret measures how much worse a decision was compared to the best possible choice in hindsight. In this setting, lower regret means the model consistently made decisions that were close to optimal. Gensyn uses time-averaged regret to track how well models perform during training. Swarm-trained models show consistently lower regret, meaning they learn faster, make fewer mistakes, and adapt more effectively with each iteration.

Gensyn’s broader goal is to build the infrastructure for permissionless decentralized training. This includes their EVM Layer-2 testnet, which tracks contributions and coordinates incentives. RL Swarm stands as one of the most promising experiments in distributed model improvement, not by brute force but by letting small models learn together, argue, revise, and grow.

Simplified takeaways in plain English:

  • Gensyn’s RL Swarm lets small models train together over regular internet connections without needing fancy data centers.
  • Models first try solving problems, then review and improve each other’s answers like a study group of AI.
  • This back-and-forth helps the models learn faster and make smarter decisions over time.
  • The system tracks how helpful each participant is and rewards them fairly, all without central control.

Nous Research

Nous Research and their Hermes 3 model family are receiving attention due to a recent release. However, the more significant development is the decentralized pretraining of a 15-billion-parameter language model using a novel optimizer and communication stack. This feat represents one of the earliest empirical demonstrations that high-performance LLM training can occur outside the confines of tightly coupled, centralized GPU clusters.

The system is built on two core innovations: DisTrO, short for Distributed Training Optimization, and the Psyche Network.

DisTrO is a method that helps computers share training progress using much less internet bandwidth than usual. Normally, when training a large model, machines need to constantly send updates to each other. These updates describe how the model is learning and adjusting with each step. In a traditional setup, these values are sent in full, which only works well inside high-speed data centers. DisTrO changes this by compressing the information before sending it.

It does this using a mathematical process called the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT), which turns long, detailed numbers into simpler summaries. Then, only the most important pieces, the top components, are shared between machines. A second technique called 1-bit quantization reduces this even further by sending just the direction of change (positive or negative), not the full number. Together, these methods cut down communication needs by thousands of times, making it possible to train models over regular internet connections instead of needing expensive infrastructure. This system was tested on a large scale. Nous’s decentralized training occurred across a diverse set of data centers in North America and Europe, including contributions from Oracle, Lambda Labs, Northern Data Group, Crusoe Cloud, and the Andromeda Cluster.

The Psyche Network on DisTrO acts as the coordination layer for decentralized training. While DisTrO handles low-bandwidth communication between machines, Psyche manages the workflow: assigning tasks, verifying progress, and recovering from failures if something goes wrong. It runs on the Solana blockchain and uses smart contracts to track training steps and ensure transparency.

Training happens in rounds. Each machine receives a task, trains on a portion of the model, saves its work, and helps verify the work of others. Psyche uses peer-to-peer networking to allow machines to connect directly, even across different networks. To maintain security and trust, it includes filters and comparison checks that flag bad data or suspicious behavior. This ensures the system stays reliable, even with many different machines involved.. This ensures the system stays reliable, even with many different machines involved.

Psyche is already being used in practice. It is currently coordinating the training of Consilience, a 40-billion parameter model using Multi-head Latent Attention (MLA), trained on 20 trillion tokens. This is one of the largest decentralized pretraining runs ever attempted. While the machines doing the work still belong to centralized cloud providers, the coordination system itself is fully decentralized and open. In the future, this framework could support more permissionless contributors, allowing anyone with the right hardware to join the training process.

To visualize this, consider a typical centralized setup: a large cluster of GPUs, all located within the same data center, constantly exchanging gradients with minimal delay. The process is efficient but extremely expensive and centralized. Now, imagine breaking that cluster apart and spreading the GPUs across various regions and vendors. Each machine still trains part of the model, but instead of communicating entire gradients at full precision, they compress those updates and reconstruct what is needed on the other side. Psyche enhances this by letting nodes continue training on new data while simultaneously sharing compressed results from the previous step, overlapping compute and communication to keep GPUs busy.

Simplified takeaways in plain English:

  • You don’t need a data center to train big models anymore. DisTrO lets computers talk to each other using highly compressed updates, slashing the bandwidth normally required.
  • Psyche acts like a decentralized manager. It keeps the system running smoothly, assigns tasks, and verifies that no one is cheating, all without a central server.
  • Even if your computer isn’t powerful, you can still help. You just train a piece of the model and share compressed updates, which the system uses to build the full model.
  • Training happens across the internet. Data centers in North America and Europe contributed to the run, with no need for high-speed fiber or specialized interconnects.
  • Verification is built-in. Psyche checks that the results are valid by comparing output from different nodes. It uses math, not trust.

Together, Nous’s work with DisTrO and Psyche represents a meaningful step toward scalable, decentralized foundation model training, bringing the compute architecture closer to the decentralization ideals many projects only gesture toward.

The Economic Thesis: It’s Not “Big AI vs. the Rest”

There are a lot of smart people working on revolutionary tech, but what does it take to succeed on an economic level? For decentralized AI to move beyond hobbyist experimentation and become a durable part of the AI landscape, there needs to be meaningful demand. Fortunately, the market is massive. PwC estimates that AI will contribute $15.7 trillion to the global economy by 2030. Big Tech will dominate most of that value through enterprise integrations, SaaS models, and embedded infrastructure, but even capturing 5% of that total, roughly $785 billion, would provide ample room for decentralized ecosystems to thrive. For perspective, that market share is the size of the GDP of a mid-sized country.

What’s important to understand is that economic viability doesn’t require winning the whole market. The goal is not to outcompete OpenAI or Google on every front; it’s to carve out a resilient alternative that serves different needs. Decentralized AI does not need a majority market share to be impactful; it needs a modest but defensible market share with sustainable economics. Consider how open source software operates today: it doesn’t dominate user-facing markets, but it undergirds much of the internet, cloud infrastructure, and developer tooling. A similar trajectory is possible for decentralized AI: infrastructure that supports inference microservices, on-demand fine-tuning, and specialized models for underserved domains.

From an economic strategy perspective, decentralized AI also enjoys cost advantages in certain areas. It can operate leaner by crowdsourcing compute, avoiding data center overhead, and leveraging crypto-native funding models. However, these benefits only matter if distribution is solved. Open infrastructure needs open access to users, developers, and tools. Monetization through inference marketplaces, verifiable computation, and modular agents could support long-tail applications that centralized labs overlook. In that sense, even “scraps” from Big AI’s table could feed an entire decentralized economy.

We also need to be honest about human behavior. From a philosophical perspective, this movement will likely remain smaller, at least for the foreseeable future. Most people don’t deeply care about decentralization. They value convenience over sovereignty. We all use iPhones, sync our lives to Google Drive, and let Facebook scan our faces. The masses have already shown that they are willing to exchange autonomy for ease, often willingly. So it’s unlikely that decentralized AI will replace the mainstream, at least not on ideology alone.

Instead, these projects need to focus on making their products easy to use. The front-facing experience should be clean, functional, and accessible. The philosophical messaging can stay under the hood because those who care about decentralization already understand its value.

Coexistence > Confrontation.

As Sun Tzu wrote in The Art of War, “Avoid what is strong. Attack what is weak.” The decentralized AI movement should not seek head-on battles with trillion-dollar companies. Instead, it should win where centralization cannot compete; by being agile, open, and aligned with emerging use cases that require trustless infrastructure. Still, opportunity alone does not guarantee success. Even if the market is large enough to support alternatives, the decentralized AI movement must navigate its own internal challenges. The greatest threats may not come from external competitors but from within, through misaligned incentives, technical fragility, or strategic overreach.

Some additional risks to consider include:

1. The pace of centralized scaling is exponential.

  • GPT-1 launched in 2018 with 117 million parameters.
  • GPT-2 expanded that to 1.5 billion in 2019.
  • GPT-3, released in 2020, made a leap to 175 billion parameters.
  • GPT-4, introduced in 2023, is rumored to contain 1.76 trillion parameters.

Each iteration has grown roughly 10x in scale, alongside performance improvements and growing user adoption. In comparison, Nous Research’s 15 billion parameter model, while a milestone for decentralized training, remains orders of magnitude behind. Centralized AI benefits from economies of scale, massive capital, and a unified engineering focus. If decentralized models cannot close the quality gap fast enough, user expectations will default toward the more powerful, polished option.

2. Model ownership remains the movement’s weakest link.

Most decentralized projects still depend on pretrained models from centralized entities like Meta (LLaMA) or OpenAI. This creates a single point of failure that undermines the entire decentralization thesis. If these upstream providers change their terms, revoke access, or modify license restrictions, entire ecosystems could be rendered inoperable overnight. Without community-owned weights, trained from scratch and governed by public protocols, decentralization breaks at the root. Projects must begin investing in training their own foundational models to truly secure independence and resilience.

3. UX matters more than ideology, and right now, Big AI wins.

ChatGPT’s success is not just about model performance; it’s about usability. The product is intuitive, fast, and requires no technical expertise. Decentralized projects often overlook this. Clunky interfaces, confusing onboarding, and fragmented tooling turn away potential users. To compete, decentralized AI needs to be as seamless to use as its centralized counterparts, or it will remain the domain of developers and idealists only.

4. A lack of focus can kill promising projects.

One common failure mode in crypto-adjacent startups is overextension. Many teams pursue too many ideas at once, training infrastructure, agents, marketplace layers, governance tools, without a clear roadmap or priority. While iteration and pivoting are healthy, trying to ship everything simultaneously leads to half-built features, scattered messaging, and burnout. A successful decentralized AI project needs a sharp thesis, clear milestones, and the discipline to say no to every shiny new idea that doesn’t advance the core mission.

5. Toxic VC incentives can hollow out real innovation.

Crypto’s history is littered with pump-and-dump schemes disguised as innovation. If AI tokens follow the same path, launching with manipulative vesting schedules, rewarding insiders disproportionately, and exiting on hype, the sector could implode before it matures. Decentralized AI projects need to consciously avoid these traps: long-term alignment, fair token launches, and real contributor incentives must replace extractive capital cycles. If not, AI could become just another speculative buzzword rather than a transformative technology.

This is not a war for dominance. It’s the creation of a parallel AI economy with its own assumptions, values, and structure. Centralized AI will continue scaling vertically—bigger models, tighter control. Decentralized AI will grow horizontally through composability, trustless coordination, and permissionless participation. Both have a role to play, but only one gives its users a stake in the system they’re helping to build.

Still, ideals alone will not drive adoption. To succeed, this ecosystem must deliver clear utility: fast and usable products that solve real problems without requiring users to care about decentralization. If the frontend fails, the backend philosophy does not matter. If token incentives distort the mission, credibility is lost. If reliance on centralized models continues, resilience remains an illusion.

But none of this negates the opportunity. The AI market is vast, and a small, focused share is enough to build a lasting alternative. The playbook is not to fight trillion-dollar labs directly, but to move in the gaps where centralization reaches its limits and provide products people can really use. That is where this movement can win.
